[_Trypanosoma cruzi_ causing Chagas diseases is uncommon in northern Mexico (Escamilla-Guerrero G, et al. Trypanosoma cruzi: seroprevalence detected in the blood bank of the Instituto Nacional de Pediatria, Mexico City, in the period 2004 through 2009. Transfusion. 2012;52(3):595-600), but with increasing density of the triatome vector in the southern United States the risk of human infection could increase. Indeed ProMED-mail reported a human case apparently infected in Louisiana in 2007. However, the risk of infection depends on contact between humans and the vector.

A recent study from the southern United States reported 7 known autochthonous human cases of Chagas plus 16 new presumed cases (Reisenman CE, et al. The distribution and abundance of triatomine insects, potential vectors of Chagas disease, in a metropolitan area in southern Arizona, United States. J Med Entomol. 2012;49(6):1254-61). The study also reported that "55-60 per cent of the triatomines were collected inside houses, and 30-35 per cent of those were found in or near beds; thus, it is likely that they fed on humans." - Mod.EP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1mfK.]
